That "tales of the glories of Christmases long, long ago" line is probably one of the most evocative lyrics in a song ever. Immediately sets your imagination off.

Like you can imagine some 18th century German village where a poor orphan family didn't have a Christmas tree and a hunter went into the forest on Christmas eve and came back a few hours later with one to bring them joy or something. The Christmas truces of the Great War in 1914.

The Japanese have an unusual reverence for school as an institution, they regarded it as one of the most important Western inventions and even Hirohito had to attend a "princely" school. You can even see this in anime, e.g. in how the Evangelion pilots still had to go to school.

A lot of emphasis is put on the interactions between children and "war games" they play, e.g. Hirohito's brother wanted to lose on purpose to the crown prince whenever wrestling, but their father told him not to do it because he wanted Hirohito to grow up tough. Stuff like this.

One of the most interesting Dr. Ray Peat paragraphs imo. On the visual similarities between breast cancer and breast tuberculosis and unsaturated fats produced by M. tb inhibiting proteolytic enzymes. Reminds me of that Uriah thread connecting Leprosy with fatty fish consumption.

The Uriah thread basically concluded areas with very high fish consumption diets had more leprosy and less tuberculosis, both of them caused by different mycobacteria species... Seems like fats really play a big role in these diseases
